6515 S.Diag(PAttr.getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_attribute_exact)
6516 << PAttr.getName();
6517 return true;
6518 }
6519
6520 // You cannot have both __sptr and __uptr on the same type, nor can you
6521 // have __ptr32 and __ptr64.
6522 if ((CurAttrKind == attr::Ptr32 && NewAttrKind == attr::Ptr64) ||
6523 (CurAttrKind == attr::Ptr64 && NewAttrKind == attr::Ptr32)) {
6524 S.Diag(PAttr.getLoc(), diag::err_attributes_are_not_compatible)
6525 << "'__ptr32'" << "'__ptr64'";
6526 return true;
6527 } else if ((CurAttrKind == attr::SPtr && NewAttrKind == attr::UPtr) ||
6528 (CurAttrKind == attr::UPtr && NewAttrKind == attr::SPtr)) {
6529 S.Diag(PAttr.getLoc(), diag::err_attributes_are_not_compatible)
6530 << "'__sptr'" << "'__uptr'";
6531 return true;
6532 }
6533
6534 Desugared = AT->getEquivalentType();
6535 AT = dyn_cast<AttributedType>(Desugared);
6536 }
6537
6538 // Pointer type qualifiers can only operate on pointer types, but not
6539 // pointer-to-member types.
6540 //
6541 // FIXME: Should we really be disallowing this attribute if there is any
6542 // type sugar between it and the pointer (other than attributes)? Eg, this
6543 // disallows the attribute on a parenthesized pointer.
6544 // And if so, should we really allow *any* type attribute?
6545 if (!isa<PointerType>(Desugared)) {
6546 if (Type->isMemberPointerType())
6547 S.Diag(PAttr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_no_member_pointers) << PAttr;
6548 else
6549 S.Diag(PAttr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_pointers_only) << PAttr << 0;
6550 return true;
6551 }
6552
6553 Type = State.getAttributedType(A, Type, Type);
6554 return false;
6555}
6556
6557/// Map a nullability attribute kind to a nullability kind.
6558static NullabilityKind mapNullabilityAttrKind(ParsedAttr::Kind kind) {
6559 switch (kind) {
6560 case ParsedAttr::AT_TypeNonNull:
6561 return NullabilityKind::NonNull;
6562
6563 case ParsedAttr::AT_TypeNullable:
6564 return NullabilityKind::Nullable;
6565
6566 case ParsedAttr::AT_TypeNullUnspecified:
6567 return NullabilityKind::Unspecified;
6568
6569 default:
6570 llvm_unreachable("not a nullability attribute kind");
6571 }
6572}
6573
6574/// Applies a nullability type specifier to the given type, if possible.
6575///
6576/// \param state The type processing state.
6577///
6578/// \param type The type to which the nullability specifier will be
6579/// added. On success, this type will be updated appropriately.
6580///
6581/// \param attr The attribute as written on the type.
6582///
6583/// \param allowOnArrayType Whether to accept nullability specifiers on an
6584/// array type (e.g., because it will decay to a pointer).
6585///
6586/// \returns true if a problem has been diagnosed, false on success.
6587static bool checkNullabilityTypeSpecifier(TypeProcessingState &state,
6588 QualType &type,
6589 ParsedAttr &attr,
6590 bool allowOnArrayType) {
6591 Sema &S = state.getSema();
6592
6593 NullabilityKind nullability = mapNullabilityAttrKind(attr.getKind());
6594 SourceLocation nullabilityLoc = attr.getLoc();
6595 bool isContextSensitive = attr.isContextSensitiveKeywordAttribute();
6596
6597 recordNullabilitySeen(S, nullabilityLoc);
6598
6599 // Check for existing nullability attributes on the type.
6600 QualType desugared = type;
6601 while (auto attributed = dyn_cast<AttributedType>(desugared.getTypePtr())) {
6602 // Check whether there is already a null
6603 if (auto existingNullability = attributed->getImmediateNullability()) {
6604 // Duplicated nullability.
6605 if (nullability == *existingNullability) {
6606 S.Diag(nullabilityLoc, diag::warn_nullability_duplicate)
6607 << DiagNullabilityKind(nullability, isContextSensitive)
6608 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(nullabilityLoc);
6609
6610 break;
6611 }
6612
6613 // Conflicting nullability.
6614 S.Diag(nullabilityLoc, diag::err_nullability_conflicting)
6615 << DiagNullabilityKind(nullability, isContextSensitive)
6616 << DiagNullabilityKind(*existingNullability, false);
6617 return true;
6618 }
6619
6620 desugared = attributed->getModifiedType();
6621 }
6622
6623 // If there is already a different nullability specifier, complain.
6624 // This (unlike the code above) looks through typedefs that might
6625 // have nullability specifiers on them, which means we cannot
6626 // provide a useful Fix-It.
6627 if (auto existingNullability = desugared->getNullability(S.Context)) {
6628 if (nullability != *existingNullability) {
6629 S.Diag(nullabilityLoc, diag::err_nullability_conflicting)
6630 << DiagNullabilityKind(nullability, isContextSensitive)
6631 << DiagNullabilityKind(*existingNullability, false);
6632
6633 // Try to find the typedef with the existing nullability specifier.
6634 if (auto typedefType = desugared->getAs<TypedefType>()) {
6635 TypedefNameDecl *typedefDecl = typedefType->getDecl();
6636 QualType underlyingType = typedefDecl->getUnderlyingType();
6637 if (auto typedefNullability
6638 = AttributedType::stripOuterNullability(underlyingType)) {
6639 if (*typedefNullability == *existingNullability) {
6640 S.Diag(typedefDecl->getLocation(), diag::note_nullability_here)
6641 << DiagNullabilityKind(*existingNullability, false);
6642 }
6643 }
6644 }
6645
6646 return true;
6647 }
6648 }
6649
6650 // If this definitely isn't a pointer type, reject the specifier.
6651 if (!desugared->canHaveNullability() &&
6652 !(allowOnArrayType && desugared->isArrayType())) {
6653 S.Diag(nullabilityLoc, diag::err_nullability_nonpointer)
6654 << DiagNullabilityKind(nullability, isContextSensitive) << type;
6655 return true;
6656 }
6657
6658 // For the context-sensitive keywords/Objective-C property
6659 // attributes, require that the type be a single-level pointer.
6660 if (isContextSensitive) {
6661 // Make sure that the pointee isn't itself a pointer type.
6662 const Type *pointeeType;
6663 if (desugared->isArrayType())
6664 pointeeType = desugared->getArrayElementTypeNoTypeQual();
6665 else
6666 pointeeType = desugared->getPointeeType().getTypePtr();
6667
6668 if (pointeeType->isAnyPointerType() ||
6669 pointeeType->isObjCObjectPointerType() ||
6670 pointeeType->isMemberPointerType()) {
6671 S.Diag(nullabilityLoc, diag::err_nullability_cs_multilevel)
6672 << DiagNullabilityKind(nullability, true)
6673 << type;
6674 S.Diag(nullabilityLoc, diag::note_nullability_type_specifier)
6675 << DiagNullabilityKind(nullability, false)
6676 << type
6677 << FixItHint::CreateReplacement(nullabilityLoc,
6678 getNullabilitySpelling(nullability));
6679 return true;
6680 }
6681 }
6682
6683 // Form the attributed type.
6684 type = state.getAttributedType(
6685 createNullabilityAttr(S.Context, attr, nullability), type, type);
6686 return false;
6687}
6688
6689/// Check the application of the Objective-C '__kindof' qualifier to
6690/// the given type.
6691static bool checkObjCKindOfType(TypeProcessingState &state, QualType &type,
6692 ParsedAttr &attr) {
6693 Sema &S = state.getSema();
6694
6695 if (isa<ObjCTypeParamType>(type)) {
6696 // Build the attributed type to record where __kindof occurred.
6697 type = state.getAttributedType(
6698 createSimpleAttr<ObjCKindOfAttr>(S.Context, attr), type, type);
6699 return false;
6700 }
6701
6702 // Find out if it's an Objective-C object or object pointer type;
6703 const ObjCObjectPointerType *ptrType = type->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
6704 const ObjCObjectType *objType = ptrType ? ptrType->getObjectType()
6705 : type->getAs<ObjCObjectType>();
6706
6707 // If not, we can't apply __kindof.
6708 if (!objType) {
6709 // FIXME: Handle dependent types that aren't yet object types.
6710 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_objc_kindof_nonobject)
6711 << type;
6712 return true;
6713 }
6714
6715 // Rebuild the "equivalent" type, which pushes __kindof down into
6716 // the object type.
6717 // There is no need to apply kindof on an unqualified id type.
6718 QualType equivType = S.Context.getObjCObjectType(
6719 objType->getBaseType(), objType->getTypeArgsAsWritten(),
6720 objType->getProtocols(),
6721 /*isKindOf=*/objType->isObjCUnqualifiedId() ? false : true);
6722
6723 // If we started with an object pointer type, rebuild it.
6724 if (ptrType) {
6725 equivType = S.Context.getObjCObjectPointerType(equivType);
6726 if (auto nullability = type->getNullability(S.Context)) {
6727 // We create a nullability attribute from the __kindof attribute.
6728 // Make sure that will make sense.
6729 assert(attr.getAttributeSpellingListIndex() == 0 &&
6730 "multiple spellings for __kindof?");
6731 Attr *A = createNullabilityAttr(S.Context, attr, *nullability);
6732 A->setImplicit(true);
6733 equivType = state.getAttributedType(A, equivType, equivType);
6734 }
6735 }
6736
6737 // Build the attributed type to record where __kindof occurred.
6738 type = state.getAttributedType(
6739 createSimpleAttr<ObjCKindOfAttr>(S.Context, attr), type, equivType);
6740 return false;
6741}
6742
6743/// Distribute a nullability type attribute that cannot be applied to
6744/// the type specifier to a pointer, block pointer, or member pointer
6745/// declarator, complaining if necessary.
6746///
6747/// \returns true if the nullability annotation was distributed, false
6748/// otherwise.
6749static bool distributeNullabilityTypeAttr(TypeProcessingState &state,
6750 QualType type, ParsedAttr &attr) {
6751 Declarator &declarator = state.getDeclarator();
6752
6753 /// Attempt to move the attribute to the specified chunk.
6754 auto moveToChunk = [&](DeclaratorChunk &chunk, bool inFunction) -> bool {
6755 // If there is already a nullability attribute there, don't add
6756 // one.
6757 if (hasNullabilityAttr(chunk.getAttrs()))
6758 return false;
6759
6760 // Complain about the nullability qualifier being in the wrong
6761 // place.
6762 enum {
6763 PK_Pointer,
6764 PK_BlockPointer,
6765 PK_MemberPointer,
6766 PK_FunctionPointer,
6767 PK_MemberFunctionPointer,
6768 } pointerKind
6769 = chunk.Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Pointer ? (inFunction ? PK_FunctionPointer
6770 : PK_Pointer)
6771 : chunk.Kind == DeclaratorChunk::BlockPointer ? PK_BlockPointer
6772 : inFunction? PK_MemberFunctionPointer : PK_MemberPointer;
6773
6774 auto diag = state.getSema().Diag(attr.getLoc(),
6775 diag::warn_nullability_declspec)
6776 << DiagNullabilityKind(mapNullabilityAttrKind(attr.getKind()),
6777 attr.isContextSensitiveKeywordAttribute())
6778 << type
6779 << static_cast<unsigned>(pointerKind);
6780
6781 // FIXME: MemberPointer chunks don't carry the location of the *.
6782 if (chunk.Kind != DeclaratorChunk::MemberPointer) {
6783 diag << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(attr.getLoc())
6784 << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(
6785 state.getSema().getPreprocessor()
6786 .getLocForEndOfToken(chunk.Loc),
6787 " " + attr.getName()->getName().str() + " ");
6788 }
6789
6790 moveAttrFromListToList(attr, state.getCurrentAttributes(),
6791 chunk.getAttrs());
6792 return true;
6793 };
6794
6795 // Move it to the outermost pointer, member pointer, or block
6796 // pointer declarator.
6797 for (unsigned i = state.getCurrentChunkIndex(); i != 0; --i) {
6798 DeclaratorChunk &chunk = declarator.getTypeObject(i-1);
6799 switch (chunk.Kind) {
6800 case DeclaratorChunk::Pointer:
6801 case DeclaratorChunk::BlockPointer:
6802 case DeclaratorChunk::MemberPointer:
6803 return moveToChunk(chunk, false);
6804
6805 case DeclaratorChunk::Paren:
6806 case DeclaratorChunk::Array:
6807 continue;
6808
6809 case DeclaratorChunk::Function:
6810 // Try to move past the return type to a function/block/member
6811 // function pointer.
6812 if (DeclaratorChunk *dest = maybeMovePastReturnType(
6813 declarator, i,
6814 /*onlyBlockPointers=*/false)) {
6815 return moveToChunk(*dest, true);
6816 }
6817
6818 return false;
6819
6820 // Don't walk through these.
6821 case DeclaratorChunk::Reference:
6822 case DeclaratorChunk::Pipe:
6823 return false;
6824 }
6825 }
6826
6827 return false;
6828}
6829
6830static Attr *getCCTypeAttr(ASTContext &Ctx, ParsedAttr &Attr) {
6831 assert(!Attr.isInvalid());
6832 switch (Attr.getKind()) {
6833 default:
6834 llvm_unreachable("not a calling convention attribute");
6835 case ParsedAttr::AT_CDecl:
6836 return createSimpleAttr<CDeclAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6837 case ParsedAttr::AT_FastCall:
6838 return createSimpleAttr<FastCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6839 case ParsedAttr::AT_StdCall:
6840 return createSimpleAttr<StdCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6841 case ParsedAttr::AT_ThisCall:
6842 return createSimpleAttr<ThisCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6843 case ParsedAttr::AT_RegCall:
6844 return createSimpleAttr<RegCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6845 case ParsedAttr::AT_Pascal:
6846 return createSimpleAttr<PascalAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6847 case ParsedAttr::AT_SwiftCall:
6848 return createSimpleAttr<SwiftCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6849 case ParsedAttr::AT_VectorCall:
6850 return createSimpleAttr<VectorCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6851 case ParsedAttr::AT_AArch64VectorPcs:
6852 return createSimpleAttr<AArch64VectorPcsAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6853 case ParsedAttr::AT_Pcs: {
6854 // The attribute may have had a fixit applied where we treated an
6855 // identifier as a string literal. The contents of the string are valid,
6856 // but the form may not be.
6857 StringRef Str;
6858 if (Attr.isArgExpr(0))
6859 Str = cast<StringLiteral>(Attr.getArgAsExpr(0))->getString();
6860 else
6861 Str = Attr.getArgAsIdent(0)->Ident->getName();
6862 PcsAttr::PCSType Type;
6863 if (!PcsAttr::ConvertStrToPCSType(Str, Type))
6864 llvm_unreachable("already validated the attribute");
6865 return ::new (Ctx) PcsAttr(Attr.getRange(), Ctx, Type,
6866 Attr.getAttributeSpellingListIndex());
6867 }
6868 case ParsedAttr::AT_CHERICCall:
6869 return createSimpleAttr<CHERICCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6870 case ParsedAttr::AT_CHERICCallee:
6871 return createSimpleAttr<CHERICCalleeAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6872 case ParsedAttr::AT_CHERICCallback:
6873 return createSimpleAttr<CHERICCallAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6874 case ParsedAttr::AT_IntelOclBicc:
6875 return createSimpleAttr<IntelOclBiccAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6876 case ParsedAttr::AT_MSABI:
6877 return createSimpleAttr<MSABIAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6878 case ParsedAttr::AT_SysVABI:
6879 return createSimpleAttr<SysVABIAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6880 case ParsedAttr::AT_PreserveMost:
6881 return createSimpleAttr<PreserveMostAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6882 case ParsedAttr::AT_PreserveAll:
6883 return createSimpleAttr<PreserveAllAttr>(Ctx, Attr);
6884 }
6885 llvm_unreachable("unexpected attribute kind!");
6886}
6887
6888/// Process an individual function attribute. Returns true to
6889/// indicate that the attribute was handled, false if it wasn't.
6890static bool handleFunctionTypeAttr(TypeProcessingState &state, ParsedAttr &attr,
6891 QualType &type) {
6892 Sema &S = state.getSema();
6893
6894 FunctionTypeUnwrapper unwrapped(S, type);
6895
6896 if (attr.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_NoReturn) {
6897 if (S.CheckAttrNoArgs(attr))
6898 return true;
6899
6900 // Delay if this is not a function type.
6901 if (!unwrapped.isFunctionType())
6902 return false;
6903
6904 // Otherwise we can process right away.
6905 FunctionType::ExtInfo EI = unwrapped.get()->getExtInfo().withNoReturn(true);
6906 type = unwrapped.wrap(S, S.Context.adjustFunctionType(unwrapped.get(), EI));
6907 return true;
6908 }
6909
6910 // ns_returns_retained is not always a type attribute, but if we got
6911 // here, we're treating it as one right now.
6912 if (attr.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_NSReturnsRetained) {
6913 if (attr.getNumArgs()) return true;
6914
6915 // Delay if this is not a function type.
6916 if (!unwrapped.isFunctionType())
6917 return false;
6918
6919 // Check whether the return type is reasonable.
6920 if (S.checkNSReturnsRetainedReturnType(attr.getLoc(),
6921 unwrapped.get()->getReturnType()))
6922 return true;
6923
6924 // Only actually change the underlying type in ARC builds.
6925 QualType origType = type;
6926 if (state.getSema().getLangOpts().ObjCAutoRefCount) {
6927 FunctionType::ExtInfo EI
6928 = unwrapped.get()->getExtInfo().withProducesResult(true);
6929 type = unwrapped.wrap(S, S.Context.adjustFunctionType(unwrapped.get(), EI));
6930 }
6931 type = state.getAttributedType(
6932 createSimpleAttr<NSReturnsRetainedAttr>(S.Context, attr),
6933 origType, type);
6934 return true;
6935 }
6936
6937 if (attr.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_AnyX86NoCallerSavedRegisters) {
6938 if (S.CheckAttrTarget(attr) || S.CheckAttrNoArgs(attr))
6939 return true;
6940
6941 // Delay if this is not a function type.
6942 if (!unwrapped.isFunctionType())
6943 return false;
6944
6945 FunctionType::ExtInfo EI =
6946 unwrapped.get()->getExtInfo().withNoCallerSavedRegs(true);
6947 type = unwrapped.wrap(S, S.Context.adjustFunctionType(unwrapped.get(), EI));
6948 return true;
6949 }
6950
6951 if (attr.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_AnyX86NoCfCheck) {
6952 if (!S.getLangOpts().CFProtectionBranch) {
6953 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::warn_nocf_check_attribute_ignored);
6954 attr.setInvalid();
6955 return true;
6956 }
6957
6958 if (S.CheckAttrTarget(attr) || S.CheckAttrNoArgs(attr))
6959 return true;
6960
6961 // If this is not a function type, warning will be asserted by subject
6962 // check.
6963 if (!unwrapped.isFunctionType())
6964 return true;
6965
6966 FunctionType::ExtInfo EI =
6967 unwrapped.get()->getExtInfo().withNoCfCheck(true);
6968 type = unwrapped.wrap(S, S.Context.adjustFunctionType(unwrapped.get(), EI));
6969 return true;
6970 }
6971
6972 if (attr.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_Regparm) {
6973 unsigned value;
6974 if (S.CheckRegparmAttr(attr, value))
6975 return true;
6976
6977 // Delay if this is not a function type.
6978 if (!unwrapped.isFunctionType())
6979 return false;
6980
6981 // Diagnose regparm with fastcall.
6982 const FunctionType *fn = unwrapped.get();
6983 CallingConv CC = fn->getCallConv();
6984 if (CC == CC_X86FastCall) {
6985 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attributes_are_not_compatible)
6986 << FunctionType::getNameForCallConv(CC)
6987 << "regparm";
6988 attr.setInvalid();
6989 return true;
6990 }
6991
6992 FunctionType::ExtInfo EI =
6993 unwrapped.get()->getExtInfo().withRegParm(value);
6994 type = unwrapped.wrap(S, S.Context.adjustFunctionType(unwrapped.get(), EI));
6995 return true;
6996 }
6997
6998 if (attr.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_NoThrow) {
6999 // Delay if this is not a function type.
7000 if (!unwrapped.isFunctionType())
7001 return false;
7002
7003 if (S.CheckAttrNoArgs(attr)) {
7004 attr.setInvalid();
7005 return true;
7006 }
7007
7008 // Otherwise we can process right away.
7009 auto *Proto = unwrapped.get()->castAs<FunctionProtoType>();
7010
7011 // MSVC ignores nothrow if it is in conflict with an explicit exception
7012 // specification.
7013 if (Proto->hasExceptionSpec()) {
7014 switch (Proto->getExceptionSpecType()) {
7015 case EST_None:
7016 llvm_unreachable("This doesn't have an exception spec!");
7017
7018 case EST_DynamicNone:
7019 case EST_BasicNoexcept:
7020 case EST_NoexceptTrue:
7021 case EST_NoThrow:
7022 // Exception spec doesn't conflict with nothrow, so don't warn.
7023 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
7024 case EST_Unparsed:
7025 case EST_Uninstantiated:
7026 case EST_DependentNoexcept:
7027 case EST_Unevaluated:
7028 // We don't have enough information to properly determine if there is a
7029 // conflict, so suppress the warning.
7030 break;
7031 case EST_Dynamic:
7032 case EST_MSAny:
7033 case EST_NoexceptFalse:
7034 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::warn_nothrow_attribute_ignored);
7035 break;
7036 }
7037 return true;
7038 }
7039
7040 type = unwrapped.wrap(
7041 S, S.Context
7042 .getFunctionTypeWithExceptionSpec(
7043 QualType{Proto, 0},
7044 FunctionProtoType::ExceptionSpecInfo{EST_NoThrow})
7045 ->getAs<FunctionType>());
7046 return true;
7047 }
7048
7049 // Delay if the type didn't work out to a function.
7050 if (!unwrapped.isFunctionType()) return false;
7051
7052 // Otherwise, a calling convention.
7053 CallingConv CC;
7054 if (S.CheckCallingConvAttr(attr, CC))
7055 return true;
7056
7057 const FunctionType *fn = unwrapped.get();
7058 CallingConv CCOld = fn->getCallConv();
7059 Attr *CCAttr = getCCTypeAttr(S.Context, attr);
7060
7061 if (CCOld != CC) {
7062 // Error out on when there's already an attribute on the type
7063 // and the CCs don't match.
7064 if (S.getCallingConvAttributedType(type)) {
7065 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attributes_are_not_compatible)
7066 << FunctionType::getNameForCallConv(CC)
7067 << FunctionType::getNameForCallConv(CCOld);
7068 attr.setInvalid();
7069 return true;
7070 }
7071 }
7072
7073 // Diagnose use of variadic functions with calling conventions that
7074 // don't support them (e.g. because they're callee-cleanup).
7075 // We delay warning about this on unprototyped function declarations
7076 // until after redeclaration checking, just in case we pick up a
7077 // prototype that way. And apparently we also "delay" warning about
7078 // unprototyped function types in general, despite not necessarily having
7079 // much ability to diagnose it later.
7080 if (!supportsVariadicCall(CC)) {
7081 const FunctionProtoType *FnP = dyn_cast<FunctionProtoType>(fn);
7082 if (FnP && FnP->isVariadic()) {
7083 // stdcall and fastcall are ignored with a warning for GCC and MS
7084 // compatibility.
7085 if (CC == CC_X86StdCall || CC == CC_X86FastCall)
7086 return S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::warn_cconv_ignored)
7087 << FunctionType::getNameForCallConv(CC)
7088 << (int)Sema::CallingConventionIgnoredReason::VariadicFunction;
7089
7090 attr.setInvalid();
7091 return S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_cconv_varargs)
7092 << FunctionType::getNameForCallConv(CC);
7093 }
7094 }
7095
7096 // Also diagnose fastcall with regparm.
7097 if (CC == CC_X86FastCall && fn->getHasRegParm()) {
7098 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attributes_are_not_compatible)
7099 << "regparm" << FunctionType::getNameForCallConv(CC_X86FastCall);
7100 attr.setInvalid();
7101 return true;
7102 }
7103
7104 // Modify the CC from the wrapped function type, wrap it all back, and then
7105 // wrap the whole thing in an AttributedType as written. The modified type
7106 // might have a different CC if we ignored the attribute.
7107 QualType Equivalent;
7108 if (CCOld == CC) {
7109 Equivalent = type;
7110 } else {
7111 auto EI = unwrapped.get()->getExtInfo().withCallingConv(CC);
7112 Equivalent =
7113 unwrapped.wrap(S, S.Context.adjustFunctionType(unwrapped.get(), EI));
7114 }
7115 type = state.getAttributedType(CCAttr, type, Equivalent);
7116 return true;
7117}
7118
7119bool Sema::hasExplicitCallingConv(QualType T) {
7120 const AttributedType *AT;
7121
7122 // Stop if we'd be stripping off a typedef sugar node to reach the
7123 // AttributedType.
7124 while ((AT = T->getAs<AttributedType>()) &&
7125 AT->getAs<TypedefType>() == T->getAs<TypedefType>()) {
7126 if (AT->isCallingConv())
7127 return true;
7128 T = AT->getModifiedType();
7129 }
7130 return false;
7131}
7132
7133void Sema::adjustMemberFunctionCC(QualType &T, bool IsStatic, bool IsCtorOrDtor,
7134 SourceLocation Loc) {
7135 FunctionTypeUnwrapper Unwrapped(*this, T);
7136 const FunctionType *FT = Unwrapped.get();
7137 bool IsVariadic = (isa<FunctionProtoType>(FT) &&
7138 cast<FunctionProtoType>(FT)->isVariadic());
7139 CallingConv CurCC = FT->getCallConv();
7140 CallingConv ToCC = Context.getDefaultCallingConvention(IsVariadic, !IsStatic);
7141
7142 if (CurCC == ToCC)
7143 return;
7144
7145 // MS compiler ignores explicit calling convention attributes on structors. We
7146 // should do the same.
7147 if (Context.getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().isMicrosoft() && IsCtorOrDtor) {
7148 // Issue a warning on ignored calling convention -- except of __stdcall.
7149 // Again, this is what MS compiler does.
7150 if (CurCC != CC_X86StdCall)
7151 Diag(Loc, diag::warn_cconv_ignored)
7152 << FunctionType::getNameForCallConv(CurCC)
7153 << (int)Sema::CallingConventionIgnoredReason::ConstructorDestructor;
7154 // Default adjustment.
7155 } else {
7156 // Only adjust types with the default convention. For example, on Windows
7157 // we should adjust a __cdecl type to __thiscall for instance methods, and a
7158 // __thiscall type to __cdecl for static methods.
7159 CallingConv DefaultCC =
7160 Context.getDefaultCallingConvention(IsVariadic, IsStatic);
7161
7162 if (CurCC != DefaultCC || DefaultCC == ToCC)
7163 return;
7164
7165 if (hasExplicitCallingConv(T))
7166 return;
7167 }
7168
7169 FT = Context.adjustFunctionType(FT, FT->getExtInfo().withCallingConv(ToCC));
7170 QualType Wrapped = Unwrapped.wrap(*this, FT);
7171 T = Context.getAdjustedType(T, Wrapped);
7172}
7173
7174/// HandleVectorSizeAttribute - this attribute is only applicable to integral
7175/// and float scalars, although arrays, pointers, and function return values are
7176/// allowed in conjunction with this construct. Aggregates with this attribute
7177/// are invalid, even if they are of the same size as a corresponding scalar.
7178/// The raw attribute should contain precisely 1 argument, the vector size for
7179/// the variable, measured in bytes. If curType and rawAttr are well formed,
7180/// this routine will return a new vector type.
7181static void HandleVectorSizeAttr(QualType &CurType, const ParsedAttr &Attr,
7182 Sema &S) {
7183 // Check the attribute arguments.
7184 if (Attr.getNumArgs() != 1) {
7185 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_wrong_number_arguments) << Attr
7186 << 1;
7187 Attr.setInvalid();
7188 return;
7189 }
7190
7191 Expr *SizeExpr;
7192 // Special case where the argument is a template id.
7193 if (Attr.isArgIdent(0)) {
7194 CXXScopeSpec SS;
7195 SourceLocation TemplateKWLoc;
7196 UnqualifiedId Id;
7197 Id.setIdentifier(Attr.getArgAsIdent(0)->Ident, Attr.getLoc());
7198
7199 ExprResult Size = S.ActOnIdExpression(S.getCurScope(), SS, TemplateKWLoc,
7200 Id, /*HasTrailingLParen=*/false,
7201 /*IsAddressOfOperand=*/false);
7202
7203 if (Size.isInvalid())
7204 return;
7205 SizeExpr = Size.get();
7206 } else {
7207 SizeExpr = Attr.getArgAsExpr(0);
7208 }
7209
7210 QualType T = S.BuildVectorType(CurType, SizeExpr, Attr.getLoc());
7211 if (!T.isNull())
7212 CurType = T;
7213 else
7214 Attr.setInvalid();
7215}
7216
7217/// Process the OpenCL-like ext_vector_type attribute when it occurs on
7218/// a type.
7219static void HandleExtVectorTypeAttr(QualType &CurType, const ParsedAttr &Attr,
7220 Sema &S) {
7221 // check the attribute arguments.
7222 if (Attr.getNumArgs() != 1) {
7223 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_wrong_number_arguments) << Attr
7224 << 1;
7225 return;
7226 }
7227
7228 Expr *sizeExpr;
7229
7230 // Special case where the argument is a template id.
7231 if (Attr.isArgIdent(0)) {
7232 CXXScopeSpec SS;
7233 SourceLocation TemplateKWLoc;
7234 UnqualifiedId id;
7235 id.setIdentifier(Attr.getArgAsIdent(0)->Ident, Attr.getLoc());
7236
7237 ExprResult Size = S.ActOnIdExpression(S.getCurScope(), SS, TemplateKWLoc,
7238 id, /*HasTrailingLParen=*/false,
7239 /*IsAddressOfOperand=*/false);
7240 if (Size.isInvalid())
7241 return;
7242
7243 sizeExpr = Size.get();
7244 } else {
7245 sizeExpr = Attr.getArgAsExpr(0);
7246 }
7247
7248 // Create the vector type.
7249 QualType T = S.BuildExtVectorType(CurType, sizeExpr, Attr.getLoc());
7250 if (!T.isNull())
7251 CurType = T;
7252}
7253
7254static bool isPermittedNeonBaseType(QualType &Ty,
7255 VectorType::VectorKind VecKind, Sema &S) {
7256 const BuiltinType *BTy = Ty->getAs<BuiltinType>();
7257 if (!BTy)
7258 return false;
7259
7260 llvm::Triple Triple = S.Context.getTargetInfo().getTriple();
7261
7262 // Signed poly is mathematically wrong, but has been baked into some ABIs by
7263 // now.
7264 bool IsPolyUnsigned = Triple.getArch() == llvm::Triple::aarch64 ||
7265 Triple.getArch() == llvm::Triple::aarch64_be;
7266 if (VecKind == VectorType::NeonPolyVector) {
7267 if (IsPolyUnsigned) {
7268 // AArch64 polynomial vectors are unsigned and support poly64.
7269 return BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::UChar ||
7270 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::UShort ||
7271 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::ULong ||
7272 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::ULongLong;
7273 } else {
7274 // AArch32 polynomial vector are signed.
7275 return BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::SChar ||
7276 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::Short;
7277 }
7278 }
7279
7280 // Non-polynomial vector types: the usual suspects are allowed, as well as
7281 // float64_t on AArch64.
7282 bool Is64Bit = Triple.getArch() == llvm::Triple::aarch64 ||
7283 Triple.getArch() == llvm::Triple::aarch64_be;
7284
7285 if (Is64Bit && BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::Double)
7286 return true;
7287
7288 return BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::SChar ||
7289 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::UChar ||
7290 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::Short ||
7291 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::UShort ||
7292 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::Int ||
7293 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::UInt ||
7294 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::Long ||
7295 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::ULong ||
7296 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::LongLong ||
7297 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::ULongLong ||
7298 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::Float ||
7299 BTy->getKind() == BuiltinType::Half;
7300}
7301
7302/// HandleNeonVectorTypeAttr - The "neon_vector_type" and
7303/// "neon_polyvector_type" attributes are used to create vector types that
7304/// are mangled according to ARM's ABI. Otherwise, these types are identical
7305/// to those created with the "vector_size" attribute. Unlike "vector_size"
7306/// the argument to these Neon attributes is the number of vector elements,
7307/// not the vector size in bytes. The vector width and element type must
7308/// match one of the standard Neon vector types.
7309static void HandleNeonVectorTypeAttr(QualType &CurType, const ParsedAttr &Attr,
7310 Sema &S, VectorType::VectorKind VecKind) {
7311 // Target must have NEON
7312 if (!S.Context.getTargetInfo().hasFeature("neon")) {
7313 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_unsupported) << Attr;
7314 Attr.setInvalid();
7315 return;
7316 }
7317 // Check the attribute arguments.
7318 if (Attr.getNumArgs() != 1) {
7319 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_wrong_number_arguments) << Attr
7320 << 1;
7321 Attr.setInvalid();
7322 return;
7323 }
7324 // The number of elements must be an ICE.
7325 Expr *numEltsExpr = static_cast<Expr *>(Attr.getArgAsExpr(0));
7326 llvm::APSInt numEltsInt(32);
7327 if (numEltsExpr->isTypeDependent() || numEltsExpr->isValueDependent() ||
7328 !numEltsExpr->isIntegerConstantExpr(numEltsInt, S.Context)) {
7329 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_argument_type)
7330 << Attr << AANT_ArgumentIntegerConstant
7331 << numEltsExpr->getSourceRange();
7332 Attr.setInvalid();
7333 return;
7334 }
7335 // Only certain element types are supported for Neon vectors.
7336 if (!isPermittedNeonBaseType(CurType, VecKind, S)) {
7337 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_invalid_vector_type) << CurType;
7338 Attr.setInvalid();
7339 return;
7340 }
7341
7342 // The total size of the vector must be 64 or 128 bits.
7343 unsigned typeSize = static_cast<unsigned>(S.Context.getTypeSize(CurType));
7344 unsigned numElts = static_cast<unsigned>(numEltsInt.getZExtValue());
7345 unsigned vecSize = typeSize * numElts;
7346 if (vecSize != 64 && vecSize != 128) {
7347 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_bad_neon_vector_size) << CurType;
7348 Attr.setInvalid();
7349 return;
7350 }
7351
7352 CurType = S.Context.getVectorType(CurType, numElts, VecKind);
7353}
7354
7355/// Handle OpenCL Access Qualifier Attribute.
7356static void HandleOpenCLAccessAttr(QualType &CurType, const ParsedAttr &Attr,
7357 Sema &S) {
7358 // OpenCL v2.0 s6.6 - Access qualifier can be used only for image and pipe type.
7359 if (!(CurType->isImageType() || CurType->isPipeType())) {
7360 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_opencl_invalid_access_qualifier);
7361 Attr.setInvalid();
7362 return;
7363 }
7364
7365 if (const TypedefType* TypedefTy = CurType->getAs<TypedefType>()) {
7366 QualType BaseTy = TypedefTy->desugar();
7367
7368 std::string PrevAccessQual;
7369 if (BaseTy->isPipeType()) {
7370 if (TypedefTy->getDecl()->hasAttr<OpenCLAccessAttr>()) {
7371 OpenCLAccessAttr *Attr =
7372 TypedefTy->getDecl()->getAttr<OpenCLAccessAttr>();
7373 PrevAccessQual = Attr->getSpelling();
7374 } else {
7375 PrevAccessQual = "read_only";
7376 }
7377 } else if (const BuiltinType* ImgType = BaseTy->getAs<BuiltinType>()) {
7378
7379 switch (ImgType->getKind()) {
7380 #define IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id, SingletonId, Access, Suffix) \
7381 case BuiltinType::Id: \
7382 PrevAccessQual = #Access; \
7383 break;
7384 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
7385 default:
7386 llvm_unreachable("Unable to find corresponding image type.");
7387 }
7388 } else {
7389 llvm_unreachable("unexpected type");
7390 }
7391 StringRef AttrName = Attr.getName()->getName();
7392 if (PrevAccessQual == AttrName.ltrim("_")) {
7393 // Duplicated qualifiers
7394 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_declspec)
7395 << AttrName << Attr.getRange();
7396 } else {
7397 // Contradicting qualifiers
7398 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_opencl_multiple_access_qualifiers);
7399 }
7400
7401 S.Diag(TypedefTy->getDecl()->getBeginLoc(),
7402 diag::note_opencl_typedef_access_qualifier) << PrevAccessQual;
7403 } else if (CurType->isPipeType()) {
7404 if (Attr.getSemanticSpelling() == OpenCLAccessAttr::Keyword_write_only) {
7405 QualType ElemType = CurType->getAs<PipeType>()->getElementType();
7406 CurType = S.Context.getWritePipeType(ElemType);
7407 }
7408 }
7409}
7410
7411/// HandleCHERICapabilityAttr - Process the cheri_capability attribute. It is
7412/// only applicable to pointer and reference types and specifies that this
7413/// pointer/reference should be treated as a capability.
7414static void HandleCHERICapabilityAttr(QualType &CurType, TypeProcessingState &state,
7415 TypeAttrLocation TAL, ParsedAttr& attr) {
7416 static bool isDeprecatedUse = false;
7417 Declarator &declarator = state.getDeclarator();
7418 Sema& S = state.getSema();
7419
7420 if (TAL == TAL_DeclName) {
7421 // TODO: we should use the spelling as written in the source
7422 // StringRef Name = attr.getName()->getName();
7423 StringRef Name = "__capability";
7424 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attr_wrong_position) << Name
7425 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(attr.getLoc())
7426 << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(state.getDeclarator().getName().getBeginLoc(), Name);
7427 return;
7428 }
7429
7430 if (TAL == TAL_DeclSpec) {
7431 // possible deprecated use; move to the outermost pointer declarator
7432 // unless this is a typedef'd pointer type
7433 if (const TypedefType *TT = CurType->getAs<TypedefType>()) {
7434 // If the underlying type is a pointer, Create a new instance of this
7435 // Typedef with a memory capability as the underlying type
7436 if (TT->isPointerType()) {
7437 CurType = S.Context.getTypedefType(TT->getDecl(), QualType(), true);
7438 return;
7439 }
7440 }
7441 isDeprecatedUse = true;
7442 for (unsigned i = state.getCurrentChunkIndex(); i != 0; --i) {
7443 DeclaratorChunk &chunk = declarator.getTypeObject(i-1);
7444 switch (chunk.Kind) {
7445 case DeclaratorChunk::Pointer: {
7446 ParsedAttr *attrCopy = declarator.getAttributePool()
7447 .create(attr.getName(), attr.getRange(),
7448 attr.getScopeName(), attr.getScopeLoc(),
7449 nullptr, 0, ParsedAttr::AS_GNU);
7450 chunk.getAttrs().addAtEnd(attrCopy);
7451 return;
7452 }
7453 case DeclaratorChunk::BlockPointer:
7454 case DeclaratorChunk::Paren:
7455 case DeclaratorChunk::Array:
7456 case DeclaratorChunk::Function:
7457 case DeclaratorChunk::Reference:
7458 case DeclaratorChunk::Pipe:
7459 continue;
7460 case DeclaratorChunk::MemberPointer:
7461 llvm_unreachable("Should this be handled?"); continue;
7462
7463 }
7464 }
7465 } else {
7466 unsigned currChunkIdx = state.getCurrentChunkIndex();
7467 DeclaratorChunk &chunk = declarator.getTypeObject(state.getCurrentChunkIndex());
7468 if (chunk.Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Pointer || chunk.Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Reference) {
7469 if (isDeprecatedUse) {
7470 // Check for an ambiguous use where this is more than one pointer
7471 // level, like __capability T **. We do this by checking that the next
7472 // chunk isn't a pointer without the attribute.
7473 if (currChunkIdx > 0) {
7474 DeclaratorChunk &nextChunk = declarator.getTypeObject(currChunkIdx-1);
7475 if (nextChunk.Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Pointer) {
7476 auto Attr = nextChunk.getAttrs();
7477 if (!Attr.hasAttribute(ParsedAttr::AT_CHERICapability)) {
7478 isDeprecatedUse = false;
7479 S.Diag(nextChunk.Loc, diag::err_cheri_capability_attribute_ambiguous);
7480 return;
7481 }
7482 }
7483 }
7484
7485 // Output a deprecated usage warning with a FixItHint
7486 SourceRange AttrRange;
7487 SourceLocation AttrLoc = attr.getLoc();
7488 if (AttrLoc.isValid()) {
7489 // The cheri_capability attribute should always be inserted via
7490 // the predefined __capability macro, but we also cater for when it
7491 // isn't in the else branch
7492 if (AttrLoc.isMacroID()) {
7493 CharSourceRange expansionRange =
7494 S.SourceMgr.getImmediateExpansionRange(AttrLoc);
7495 AttrRange.setBegin(expansionRange.getBegin());
7496 AttrRange.setEnd(expansionRange.getEnd());
7497 } else {
7498 // Calculate extended range to include the preceding
7499 // __attribute(( and following ))
7500 AttrRange.setBegin(AttrLoc.getLocWithOffset(-15));
7501 AttrRange.setEnd(AttrLoc.getLocWithOffset(18));
7502 }
7503 }
7504 S.Diag(chunk.Loc, diag::warn_cheri_capability_attribute_location)
7505 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(AttrRange)
7506 << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(chunk.Loc.getLocWithOffset(1),
7507 " __capability ");
7508 isDeprecatedUse = false;
7509 }
7510 if (CurType->isPointerType() || CurType->isReferenceType()) {
7511 // preserve existing qualifiers on CurType
7512 Qualifiers Qs = CurType.getQualifiers();
7513 if (const PointerType *PT = CurType->getAs<PointerType>())
7514 CurType = S.Context.getPointerType(PT->getPointeeType(), ASTContext::PIK_Capability);
7515 else if (const LValueReferenceType *LRT = CurType->getAs<LValueReferenceType>())
7516 CurType = S.Context.getLValueReferenceType(LRT->getPointeeType(), true, ASTContext::PIK_Capability);
7517 else if (const RValueReferenceType *RRT = CurType->getAs<RValueReferenceType>())
7518 CurType = S.Context.getRValueReferenceType(RRT->getPointeeType(), ASTContext::PIK_Capability);
7519 if (Qs.hasQualifiers())
7520 CurType = S.Context.getQualifiedType(CurType, Qs);
7521 return;
7522 }
7523 }
7524 }
7525
7526 S.Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_cheri_capability_attribute_pointers_only) << CurType;
7527}
7528
7529
7530static bool HandleMemoryAddressAttr(QualType &T, TypeProcessingState &State,
7531 TypeAttrLocation TAL, ParsedAttr& Attr) {
7532 Sema &S = State.getSema();
7533 assert(Attr.getKind() == ParsedAttr::AT_MemoryAddress);
7534 // XXXAR: FIXME: Why do I get an assertion later if I don't error out here?
7535 if (TAL == TAL_DeclName) {
7536 StringRef Name = Attr.getName()->getName();
7537 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attr_wrong_position) << Name
7538 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(Attr.getLoc())
7539 << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(State.getDeclarator().getDeclSpec().getBeginLoc(), Name);
7540 return true;
7541 }
7542
7543 if (!T->isIntegerType() || T->isCHERICapabilityType(S.Context)) {
7544 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_address_integers_only)
7545 << Attr.getName() << T;
7546 return true;
7547 }
7548
7549 // llvm::errs() << __func__ << ": hasAttr():" << T->hasAttr(attr::MemoryAddress) << " dump: "; T.dump();
7550 if (T->hasAttr(attr::MemoryAddress))
7551 S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::warn_duplicate_attribute_exact) << Attr.getName();
7552 T = State.getAttributedType(
7553 createSimpleAttr<MemoryAddressAttr>(State.getSema().Context, Attr), T, T);
7554 // llvm::errs() << __func__ << ": modified type: "; T.dump();
7555 return false;
7556}
7557
7558static void deduceOpenCLImplicitAddrSpace(TypeProcessingState &State,
7559 QualType &T, TypeAttrLocation TAL) {
7560 Declarator &D = State.getDeclarator();
7561
7562 // Handle the cases where address space should not be deduced.
7563 //
7564 // The pointee type of a pointer type is always deduced since a pointer always
7565 // points to some memory location which should has an address space.
7566 //
7567 // There are situations that at the point of certain declarations, the address
7568 // space may be unknown and better to be left as default. For example, when
7569 // defining a typedef or struct type, they are not associated with any
7570 // specific address space. Later on, they may be used with any address space
7571 // to declare a variable.
7572 //
7573 // The return value of a function is r-value, therefore should not have
7574 // address space.
7575 //
7576 // The void type does not occupy memory, therefore should not have address
7577 // space, except when it is used as a pointee type.
7578 //
7579 // Since LLVM assumes function type is in default address space, it should not
7580 // have address space.
7581 auto ChunkIndex = State.getCurrentChunkIndex();
7582 bool IsPointee =
7583 ChunkIndex > 0 &&
7584 (D.getTypeObject(ChunkIndex - 1).Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Pointer ||
7585 D.getTypeObject(ChunkIndex - 1).Kind == DeclaratorChunk::BlockPointer ||
7586 D.getTypeObject(ChunkIndex - 1).Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Reference);
7587 bool IsFuncReturnType =
7588 ChunkIndex > 0 &&
7589 D.getTypeObject(ChunkIndex - 1).Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Function;
7590 bool IsFuncType =
7591 ChunkIndex < D.getNumTypeObjects() &&
7592 D.getTypeObject(ChunkIndex).Kind == DeclaratorChunk::Function;
7593 if ( // Do not deduce addr space for function return type and function type,
7594 // otherwise it will fail some sema check.
7595 IsFuncReturnType || IsFuncType ||
7596 // Do not deduce addr space for member types of struct, except the pointee
7597 // type of a pointer member type or static data members.
7598 (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::MemberContext &&
7599 (!IsPointee &&
7600 D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpec() != DeclSpec::SCS_static)) ||
7601 // Do not deduce addr space of non-pointee in type alias because it
7602 // doesn't define any object.
7603 (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::AliasDeclContext && !IsPointee) ||
7604 // Do not deduce addr space for types used to define a typedef and the
7605 // typedef itself, except the pointee type of a pointer type which is used
7606 // to define the typedef.
7607 (D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpec() == DeclSpec::SCS_typedef &&
7608 !IsPointee) ||
7609 // Do not deduce addr space of the void type, e.g. in f(void), otherwise
7610 // it will fail some sema check.
7611 (T->isVoidType() && !IsPointee) ||
7612 // Do not deduce addr spaces for dependent types because they might end
7613 // up instantiating to a type with an explicit address space qualifier.
7614 T->isDependentType() ||
7615 // Do not deduce addr space of decltype because it will be taken from
7616 // its argument.
7617 T->isDecltypeType() ||
7618 // OpenCL spec v2.0 s6.9.b:
7619 // The sampler type cannot be used with the __local and __global address
7620 // space qualifiers.
7621 // OpenCL spec v2.0 s6.13.14:
7622 // Samplers can also be declared as global constants in the program
7623 // source using the following syntax.
7624 // const sampler_t <sampler name> = <value>
7625 // In codegen, file-scope sampler type variable has special handing and
7626 // does not rely on address space qualifier. On the other hand, deducing
7627 // address space of const sampler file-scope variable as global address
7628 // space causes spurious diagnostic about __global address space
7629 // qualifier, therefore do not deduce address space of file-scope sampler
7630 // type variable.
7631 (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::FileContext && T->isSamplerT()))
7632 return;
7633
7634 LangAS ImpAddr = LangAS::Default;
7635 // Put OpenCL automatic variable in private address space.
7636 // OpenCL v1.2 s6.5:
7637 // The default address space name for arguments to a function in a
7638 // program, or local variables of a function is __private. All function
7639 // arguments shall be in the __private address space.
7640 if (State.getSema().getLangOpts().OpenCLVersion <= 120 &&
7641 !State.getSema().getLangOpts().OpenCLCPlusPlus) {
7642 ImpAddr = LangAS::opencl_private;
7643 } else {
7644 // If address space is not set, OpenCL 2.0 defines non private default
7645 // address spaces for some cases:
7646 // OpenCL 2.0, section 6.5:
7647 // The address space for a variable at program scope or a static variable
7648 // inside a function can either be __global or __constant, but defaults to
7649 // __global if not specified.
7650 // (...)
7651 // Pointers that are declared without pointing to a named address space
7652 // point to the generic address space.
7653 if (IsPointee) {
7654 ImpAddr = LangAS::opencl_generic;
7655 } else {
7656 if (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::TemplateArgContext) {
7657 // Do not deduce address space for non-pointee type in template arg.
7658 } else if (D.getContext() == DeclaratorContext::FileContext) {
7659 ImpAddr = LangAS::opencl_global;
7660 } else {
7661 if (D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpec() == DeclSpec::SCS_static ||
7662 D.getDeclSpec().getStorageClassSpec() == DeclSpec::SCS_extern) {
7663 ImpAddr = LangAS::opencl_global;
7664 } else {
7665 ImpAddr = LangAS::opencl_private;
7666 }
7667 }
7668 }
7669 }
7670 T = State.getSema().Context.getAddrSpaceQualType(T, ImpAddr);
7671}
7672
7673static void HandleLifetimeBoundAttr(TypeProcessingState &State,
7674 QualType &CurType,
7675 ParsedAttr &Attr) {
7676 if (State.getDeclarator().isDeclarationOfFunction()) {
7677 CurType = State.getAttributedType(
7678 createSimpleAttr<LifetimeBoundAttr>(State.getSema().Context, Attr),
7679 CurType, CurType);
7680 } else {
7681 Attr.diagnoseAppertainsTo(State.getSema(), nullptr);
7682 }
7683}
7684
7685
7686static void processTypeAttrs(TypeProcessingState &state, QualType &type,
7687 TypeAttrLocation TAL,
7688 ParsedAttributesView &attrs) {
7689 // Scan through and apply attributes to this type where it makes sense. Some
7690 // attributes (such as __address_space__, __vector_size__, etc) apply to the
7691 // type, but others can be present in the type specifiers even though they
7692 // apply to the decl. Here we apply type attributes and ignore the rest.
7693
7694 // This loop modifies the list pretty frequently, but we still need to make
7695 // sure we visit every element once. Copy the attributes list, and iterate
7696 // over that.
7697 ParsedAttributesView AttrsCopy{attrs};
7698
7699 state.setParsedNoDeref(false);
7700
7701 for (ParsedAttr &attr : AttrsCopy) {
7702
7703 // Skip attributes that were marked to be invalid.
7704 if (attr.isInvalid())
7705 continue;
7706
7707 if (attr.isCXX11Attribute()) {
7708 // [[gnu::...]] attributes are treated as declaration attributes, so may
7709 // not appertain to a DeclaratorChunk. If we handle them as type
7710 // attributes, accept them in that position and diagnose the GCC
7711 // incompatibility.
7712 if (attr.isGNUScope()) {
7713 bool IsTypeAttr = attr.isTypeAttr();
7714 if (TAL == TAL_DeclChunk) {
7715 state.getSema().Diag(attr.getLoc(),
7716 IsTypeAttr
7717 ? diag::warn_gcc_ignores_type_attr
7718 : diag::warn_cxx11_gnu_attribute_on_type)
7719 << attr.getName();
7720 if (!IsTypeAttr)
7721 continue;
7722 }
7723 } else if (TAL != TAL_DeclChunk &&
7724 attr.getKind() != ParsedAttr::AT_AddressSpace) {
7725 // Otherwise, only consider type processing for a C++11 attribute if
7726 // it's actually been applied to a type.
7727 // We also allow C++11 address_space attributes to pass through.
7728 continue;
7729 }
7730 }
7731
7732 // If this is an attribute we can handle, do so now,
7733 // otherwise, add it to the FnAttrs list for rechaining.
7734 switch (attr.getKind()) {
7735 default:
7736 // A C++11 attribute on a declarator chunk must appertain to a type.
7737 if (attr.isCXX11Attribute() && TAL == TAL_DeclChunk) {
7738 state.getSema().Diag(attr.getLoc(), diag::err_attribute_not_type_attr)
7739 << attr;
7740 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7741 }
7742 break;
7743
7744 case ParsedAttr::UnknownAttribute:
7745 if (attr.isCXX11Attribute() && TAL == TAL_DeclChunk)
7746 state.getSema().Diag(attr.getLoc(),
7747 diag::warn_unknown_attribute_ignored)
7748 << attr.getName();
7749 break;
7750
7751 case ParsedAttr::IgnoredAttribute:
7752 break;
7753
7754 case ParsedAttr::AT_MayAlias:
7755 // FIXME: This attribute needs to actually be handled, but if we ignore
7756 // it it breaks large amounts of Linux software.
7757 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7758 break;
7759 case ParsedAttr::AT_OpenCLPrivateAddressSpace:
7760 case ParsedAttr::AT_OpenCLGlobalAddressSpace:
7761 case ParsedAttr::AT_OpenCLLocalAddressSpace:
7762 case ParsedAttr::AT_OpenCLConstantAddressSpace:
7763 case ParsedAttr::AT_OpenCLGenericAddressSpace:
7764 case ParsedAttr::AT_AddressSpace:
7765 HandleAddressSpaceTypeAttribute(type, attr, state);
7766 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7767 break;
7768 OBJC_POINTER_TYPE_ATTRS_CASELIST:
7769 if (!handleObjCPointerTypeAttr(state, attr, type))
7770 distributeObjCPointerTypeAttr(state, attr, type);
7771 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7772 break;
7773 case ParsedAttr::AT_VectorSize:
7774 HandleVectorSizeAttr(type, attr, state.getSema());
7775 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7776 break;
7777 case ParsedAttr::AT_ExtVectorType:
7778 HandleExtVectorTypeAttr(type, attr, state.getSema());
7779 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7780 break;
7781 case ParsedAttr::AT_NeonVectorType:
7782 HandleNeonVectorTypeAttr(type, attr, state.getSema(),
7783 VectorType::NeonVector);
7784 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7785 break;
7786 case ParsedAttr::AT_NeonPolyVectorType:
7787 HandleNeonVectorTypeAttr(type, attr, state.getSema(),
7788 VectorType::NeonPolyVector);
7789 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7790 break;
7791 case ParsedAttr::AT_OpenCLAccess:
7792 HandleOpenCLAccessAttr(type, attr, state.getSema());
7793 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7794 break;
7795 case ParsedAttr::AT_LifetimeBound:
7796 if (TAL == TAL_DeclChunk)
7797 HandleLifetimeBoundAttr(state, type, attr);
7798 break;
7799
7800 case ParsedAttr::AT_NoDeref: {
7801 ASTContext &Ctx = state.getSema().Context;
7802 type = state.getAttributedType(createSimpleAttr<NoDerefAttr>(Ctx, attr),
7803 type, type);
7804 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7805 state.setParsedNoDeref(true);
7806 break;
7807 }
7808
7809 MS_TYPE_ATTRS_CASELIST:
7810 if (!handleMSPointerTypeQualifierAttr(state, attr, type))
7811 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7812 break;
7813
7814
7815 NULLABILITY_TYPE_ATTRS_CASELIST:
7816 // Either add nullability here or try to distribute it. We
7817 // don't want to distribute the nullability specifier past any
7818 // dependent type, because that complicates the user model.
7819 if (type->canHaveNullability() || type->isDependentType() ||
7820 type->isArrayType() ||
7821 !distributeNullabilityTypeAttr(state, type, attr)) {
7822 unsigned endIndex;
7823 if (TAL == TAL_DeclChunk)
7824 endIndex = state.getCurrentChunkIndex();
7825 else
7826 endIndex = state.getDeclarator().getNumTypeObjects();
7827 bool allowOnArrayType =
7828 state.getDeclarator().isPrototypeContext() &&
7829 !hasOuterPointerLikeChunk(state.getDeclarator(), endIndex);
7830 if (checkNullabilityTypeSpecifier(
7831 state,
7832 type,
7833 attr,
7834 allowOnArrayType)) {
7835 attr.setInvalid();
7836 }
7837
7838 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7839 }
7840 break;
7841
7842 case ParsedAttr::AT_ObjCKindOf:
7843 // '__kindof' must be part of the decl-specifiers.
7844 switch (TAL) {
7845 case TAL_DeclSpec:
7846 break;
7847
7848 case TAL_DeclChunk:
7849 case TAL_DeclName:
7850 state.getSema().Diag(attr.getLoc(),
7851 diag::err_attr_wrong_position) << "__kindof"
7852 << FixItHint::CreateRemoval(attr.getLoc())
7853 << FixItHint::CreateInsertion(
7854 state.getDeclarator().getDeclSpec().getBeginLoc(),
7855 "__kindof ");
7856 break;
7857 }
7858
7859 // Apply it regardless.
7860 if (checkObjCKindOfType(state, type, attr))
7861 attr.setInvalid();
7862 break;
7863
7864 case ParsedAttr::AT_NoThrow:
7865 // Exception Specifications aren't generally supported in C mode throughout
7866 // clang, so revert to attribute-based handling for C.
7867 if (!state.getSema().getLangOpts().CPlusPlus)
7868 break;
7869 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
7870 FUNCTION_TYPE_ATTRS_CASELIST:
7871 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7872
7873 // Never process function type attributes as part of the
7874 // declaration-specifiers.
7875 if (TAL == TAL_DeclSpec)
7876 distributeFunctionTypeAttrFromDeclSpec(state, attr, type);
7877
7878 // Otherwise, handle the possible delays.
7879 else if (!handleFunctionTypeAttr(state, attr, type))
7880 distributeFunctionTypeAttr(state, attr, type);
7881 break;
7882
7883 case ParsedAttr::AT_CHERICapability:
7884 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7885 HandleCHERICapabilityAttr(type, state, TAL, attr);
7886 break;
7887 case ParsedAttr::AT_CHERINoSubobjectBounds:
7888 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7889 if (type->hasAttr(attr::CHERINoSubobjectBounds))
7890 state.getSema().Diag(attr.getLoc(),
7891 diag::warn_duplicate_attribute_exact)
7892 << attr.getName();
7893 type =
7894 state.getAttributedType(createSimpleAttr<CHERINoSubobjectBoundsAttr>(
7895 state.getSema().Context, attr),
7896 type, type);
7897 break;
7898 case ParsedAttr::AT_MemoryAddress:
7899 // llvm::errs() << "applying memory_address to "; type.dump();
7900 if (!HandleMemoryAddressAttr(type, state, TAL, attr)) {
7901 attr.setUsedAsTypeAttr();
7902 }
7903 break;
7904 }
7905
7906 // Handle attributes that are defined in a macro. We do not want this to be
7907 // applied to ObjC builtin attributes.
7908 if (isa<AttributedType>(type) && attr.hasMacroIdentifier() &&
7909 !type.getQualifiers().hasObjCLifetime() &&
7910 !type.getQualifiers().hasObjCGCAttr() &&
7911 attr.getKind() != ParsedAttr::AT_ObjCGC &&
7912 attr.getKind() != ParsedAttr::AT_ObjCOwnership) {
7913 const IdentifierInfo *MacroII = attr.getMacroIdentifier();
7914 type = state.getSema().Context.getMacroQualifiedType(type, MacroII);
7915 state.setExpansionLocForMacroQualifiedType(
7916 cast<MacroQualifiedType>(type.getTypePtr()),
7917 attr.getMacroExpansionLoc());
7918 }
7919 }
7920
7921 if (!state.getSema().getLangOpts().OpenCL ||
7922 type.getAddressSpace() != LangAS::Default)
7923 return;
7924
7925 deduceOpenCLImplicitAddrSpace(state, type, TAL);
7926}
7927
7928void Sema::completeExprArrayBound(Expr *E) {
7929 if (DeclRefExpr *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E->IgnoreParens())) {
7930 if (VarDecl *Var = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(DRE->getDecl())) {
7931 if (isTemplateInstantiation(Var->getTemplateSpecializationKind())) {
7932 auto *Def = Var->getDefinition();
7933 if (!Def) {
7934 SourceLocation PointOfInstantiation = E->getExprLoc();
7935 InstantiateVariableDefinition(PointOfInstantiation, Var);
7936 Def = Var->getDefinition();
7937
7938 // If we don't already have a point of instantiation, and we managed
7939 // to instantiate a definition, this is the point of instantiation.
7940 // Otherwise, we don't request an end-of-TU instantiation, so this is
7941 // not a point of instantiation.
7942 // FIXME: Is this really the right behavior?
7943 if (Var->getPointOfInstantiation().isInvalid() && Def) {
7944 assert(Var->getTemplateSpecializationKind() ==
7945 TSK_ImplicitInstantiation &&
7946 "explicit instantiation with no point of instantiation");
7947 Var->setTemplateSpecializationKind(
7948 Var->getTemplateSpecializationKind(), PointOfInstantiation);
7949 }
7950 }
7951
7952 // Update the type to the definition's type both here and within the
7953 // expression.
7954 if (Def) {
7955 DRE->setDecl(Def);
7956 QualType T = Def->getType();
7957 DRE->setType(T);
7958 // FIXME: Update the type on all intervening expressions.
7959 E->setType(T);
7960 }
7961
7962 // We still go on to try to complete the type independently, as it
7963 // may also require instantiations or diagnostics if it remains
7964 // incomplete.
7965 }
7966 }
7967 }
7968}
7969
7970/// Ensure that the type of the given expression is complete.
7971///
7972/// This routine checks whether the expression \p E has a complete type. If the
7973/// expression refers to an instantiable construct, that instantiation is
7974/// performed as needed to complete its type. Furthermore
7975/// Sema::RequireCompleteType is called for the expression's type (or in the
7976/// case of a reference type, the referred-to type).
7977///
7978/// \param E The expression whose type is required to be complete.
7979/// \param Diagnoser The object that will emit a diagnostic if the type is
7980/// incomplete.
7981///
7982/// \returns \c true if the type of \p E is incomplete and diagnosed, \c false
7983/// otherwise.
7984bool Sema::RequireCompleteExprType(Expr *E, TypeDiagnoser &Diagnoser) {
7985 QualType T = E->getType();
7986
7987 // Incomplete array types may be completed by the initializer attached to
7988 // their definitions. For static data members of class templates and for
7989 // variable templates, we need to instantiate the definition to get this
7990 // initializer and complete the type.
7991 if (T->isIncompleteArrayType()) {
7992 completeExprArrayBound(E);
7993 T = E->getType();
7994 }
7995
7996 // FIXME: Are there other cases which require instantiating something other
7997 // than the type to complete the type of an expression?
7998
7999 return RequireCompleteType(E->getExprLoc(), T, Diagnoser);
8000}
8001
8002bool Sema::RequireCompleteExprType(Expr *E, unsigned DiagID) {
8003 BoundTypeDiagnoser<> Diagnoser(DiagID);
8004 return RequireCompleteExprType(E, Diagnoser);
8005}
8006
8007/// Ensure that the type T is a complete type.
8008///
8009/// This routine checks whether the type @p T is complete in any
8010/// context where a complete type is required. If @p T is a complete
8011/// type, returns false. If @p T is a class template specialization,
8012/// this routine then attempts to perform class template
8013/// instantiation. If instantiation fails, or if @p T is incomplete
8014/// and cannot be completed, issues the diagnostic @p diag (giving it
8015/// the type @p T) and returns true.
8016///
8017/// @param Loc The location in the source that the incomplete type
8018/// diagnostic should refer to.
8019///
8020/// @param T The type that this routine is examining for completeness.
8021///
8022/// @returns @c true if @p T is incomplete and a diagnostic was emitted,
8023/// @c false otherwise.
8024bool Sema::RequireCompleteType(SourceLocation Loc, QualType T,
8025 TypeDiagnoser &Diagnoser) {
8026 if (RequireCompleteTypeImpl(Loc, T, &Diagnoser))
8027 return true;
8028 if (const TagType *Tag = T->getAs<TagType>()) {
8029 if (!Tag->getDecl()->isCompleteDefinitionRequired()) {
8030 Tag->getDecl()->setCompleteDefinitionRequired();
8031 Consumer.HandleTagDeclRequiredDefinition(Tag->getDecl());
8032 }
8033 }
8034 return false;
8035}
8036
8037bool Sema::hasStructuralCompatLayout(Decl *D, Decl *Suggested) {
8038 llvm::DenseSet<std::pair<Decl *, Decl *>> NonEquivalentDecls;
8039 if (!Suggested)
8040 return false;
8041
8042 // FIXME: Add a specific mode for C11 6.2.7/1 in StructuralEquivalenceContext
8043 // and isolate from other C++ specific checks.
8044 StructuralEquivalenceContext Ctx(
8045 D->getASTContext(), Suggested->getASTContext(), NonEquivalentDecls,
8046 StructuralEquivalenceKind::Default,
8047 false /*StrictTypeSpelling*/, true /*Complain*/,
8048 true /*ErrorOnTagTypeMismatch*/);
8049 return Ctx.IsEquivalent(D, Suggested);
8050}
8051
8052/// Determine whether there is any declaration of \p D that was ever a
8053/// definition (perhaps before module merging) and is currently visible.
8054/// \param D The definition of the entity.
8055/// \param Suggested Filled in with the declaration that should be made visible
8056/// in order to provide a definition of this entity.
8057/// \param OnlyNeedComplete If \c true, we only need the type to be complete,
8058/// not defined. This only matters for enums with a fixed underlying
8059/// type, since in all other cases, a type is complete if and only if it
8060/// is defined.
8061bool Sema::hasVisibleDefinition(NamedDecl *D, NamedDecl **Suggested,
8062 bool OnlyNeedComplete) {
8063 // Easy case: if we don't have modules, all declarations are visible.
8064 if (!getLangOpts().Modules && !getLangOpts().ModulesLocalVisibility)
8065 return true;
8066
8067 // If this definition was instantiated from a template, map back to the
8068 // pattern from which it was instantiated.
8069 if (isa<TagDecl>(D) && cast<TagDecl>(D)->isBeingDefined()) {
8070 // We're in the middle of defining it; this definition should be treated
8071 // as visible.
8072 return true;
8073 } else if (auto *RD = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(D)) {
8074 if (auto *Pattern = RD->getTemplateInstantiationPattern())
8075 RD = Pattern;
8076 D = RD->getDefinition();
8077 } else if (auto *ED = dyn_cast<EnumDecl>(D)) {
8078 if (auto *Pattern = ED->getTemplateInstantiationPattern())
8079 ED = Pattern;
8080 if (OnlyNeedComplete && ED->isFixed()) {
8081 // If the enum has a fixed underlying type, and we're only looking for a
8082 // complete type (not a definition), any visible declaration of it will
8083 // do.
8084 *Suggested = nullptr;
8085 for (auto *Redecl : ED->redecls()) {
8086 if (isVisible(Redecl))
8087 return true;
8088 if (Redecl->isThisDeclarationADefinition() ||
8089 (Redecl->isCanonicalDecl() && !*Suggested))
8090 *Suggested = Redecl;
8091 }
8092 return false;
8093 }
8094 D = ED->getDefinition();
8095 } else if (auto *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(D)) {
8096 if (auto *Pattern = FD->getTemplateInstantiationPattern())
8097 FD = Pattern;
8098 D = FD->getDefinition();
8099 } else if (auto *VD = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(D)) {
8100 if (auto *Pattern = VD->getTemplateInstantiationPattern())
8101 VD = Pattern;
8102 D = VD->getDefinition();
8103 }
8104 assert(D && "missing definition for pattern of instantiated definition");
8105
8106 *Suggested = D;
8107
8108 auto DefinitionIsVisible = [&] {
8109 // The (primary) definition might be in a visible module.
8110 if (isVisible(D))
8111 return true;
8112
8113 // A visible module might have a merged definition instead.
8114 if (D->isModulePrivate() ? hasMergedDefinitionInCurrentModule(D)
8115 : hasVisibleMergedDefinition(D)) {
8116 if (CodeSynthesisContexts.empty() &&
8117 !getLangOpts().ModulesLocalVisibility) {
8118 // Cache the fact that this definition is implicitly visible because
8119 // there is a visible merged definition.
8120 D->setVisibleDespiteOwningModule();
8121 }
8122 return true;
8123 }
8124
8125 return false;
8126 };
8127
8128 if (DefinitionIsVisible())
8129 return true;
8130
8131 // The external source may have additional definitions of this entity that are
8132 // visible, so complete the redeclaration chain now and ask again.
8133 if (auto *Source = Context.getExternalSource()) {
8134 Source->CompleteRedeclChain(D);
8135 return DefinitionIsVisible();
8136 }
8137
8138 return false;
8139}
8140
8141/// Locks in the inheritance model for the given class and all of its bases.
8142static void assignInheritanceModel(Sema &S, CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
8143 RD = RD->getMostRecentNonInjectedDecl();
8144 if (!RD->hasAttr<MSInheritanceAttr>()) {
8145 MSInheritanceAttr::Spelling IM;
8146
8147 switch (S.MSPointerToMemberRepresentationMethod) {
8148 case LangOptions::PPTMK_BestCase:
8149 IM = RD->calculateInheritanceModel();
8150 break;
8151 case LangOptions::PPTMK_FullGeneralitySingleInheritance:
8152 IM = MSInheritanceAttr::Keyword_single_inheritance;
8153 break;
8154 case LangOptions::PPTMK_FullGeneralityMultipleInheritance:
8155 IM = MSInheritanceAttr::Keyword_multiple_inheritance;
8156 break;
8157 case LangOptions::PPTMK_FullGeneralityVirtualInheritance:
8158 IM = MSInheritanceAttr::Keyword_unspecified_inheritance;
8159 break;
8160 }
8161
8162 RD->addAttr(MSInheritanceAttr::CreateImplicit(
8163 S.getASTContext(), IM,
8164 /*BestCase=*/S.MSPointerToMemberRepresentationMethod ==
8165 LangOptions::PPTMK_BestCase,
8166 S.ImplicitMSInheritanceAttrLoc.isValid()
8167 ? S.ImplicitMSInheritanceAttrLoc
8168 : RD->getSourceRange()));
8169 S.Consumer.AssignInheritanceModel(RD);
8170 }
8171}
8172
8173/// The implementation of RequireCompleteType
8174bool Sema::RequireCompleteTypeImpl(SourceLocation Loc, QualType T,
8175 TypeDiagnoser *Diagnoser) {
8176 // FIXME: Add this assertion to make sure we always get instantiation points.
8177 // assert(!Loc.isInvalid() && "Invalid location in RequireCompleteType");
8178 // FIXME: Add this assertion to help us flush out problems with
8179 // checking for dependent types and type-dependent expressions.
8180 //
8181 // assert(!T->isDependentType() &&
8182 // "Can't ask whether a dependent type is complete");
8183
8184 if (const MemberPointerType *MPTy = T->getAs<MemberPointerType>()) {
8185 if (!MPTy->getClass()->isDependentType()) {
8186 if (getLangOpts().CompleteMemberPointers &&
8187 !MPTy->getClass()->getAsCXXRecordDecl()->isBeingDefined() &&
8188 RequireCompleteType(Loc, QualType(MPTy->getClass(), 0),
8189 diag::err_memptr_incomplete))
8190 return true;
8191
8192 // We lock in the inheritance model once somebody has asked us to ensure
8193 // that a pointer-to-member type is complete.
8194 if (Context.getTargetInfo().getCXXABI().isMicrosoft()) {
8195 (void)isCompleteType(Loc, QualType(MPTy->getClass(), 0));
8196 assignInheritanceModel(*this, MPTy->getMostRecentCXXRecordDecl());
8197 }
8198 }
8199 }
8200
8201 NamedDecl *Def = nullptr;
8202 bool Incomplete = T->isIncompleteType(&Def);
8203
8204 // Check that any necessary explicit specializations are visible. For an
8205 // enum, we just need the declaration, so don't check this.
8206 if (Def && !isa<EnumDecl>(Def))
8207 checkSpecializationVisibility(Loc, Def);
8208
8209 // If we have a complete type, we're done.
8210 if (!Incomplete) {
8211 // If we know about the definition but it is not visible, complain.
8212 NamedDecl *SuggestedDef = nullptr;
8213 if (Def &&
8214 !hasVisibleDefinition(Def, &SuggestedDef, /*OnlyNeedComplete*/true)) {
8215 // If the user is going to see an error here, recover by making the
8216 // definition visible.
8217 bool TreatAsComplete = Diagnoser && !isSFINAEContext();
8218 if (Diagnoser && SuggestedDef)
8219 diagnoseMissingImport(Loc, SuggestedDef, MissingImportKind::Definition,
8220 /*Recover*/TreatAsComplete);
8221 return !TreatAsComplete;
8222 } else if (Def && !TemplateInstCallbacks.empty()) {
8223 CodeSynthesisContext TempInst;
8224 TempInst.Kind = CodeSynthesisContext::Memoization;
8225 TempInst.Template = Def;
8226 TempInst.Entity = Def;
8227 TempInst.PointOfInstantiation = Loc;
8228 atTemplateBegin(TemplateInstCallbacks, *this, TempInst);
8229 atTemplateEnd(TemplateInstCallbacks, *this, TempInst);
8230 }
8231
8232 return false;
8233 }
8234
8235 TagDecl *Tag = dyn_cast_or_null<TagDecl>(Def);
8236 ObjCInterfaceDecl *IFace = dyn_cast_or_null<ObjCInterfaceDecl>(Def);
8237
8238 // Give the external source a chance to provide a definition of the type.
8239 // This is kept separate from completing the redeclaration chain so that
8240 // external sources such as LLDB can avoid synthesizing a type definition
8241 // unless it's actually needed.
8242 if (Tag || IFace) {
8243 // Avoid diagnosing invalid decls as incomplete.
8244 if (Def->isInvalidDecl())
8245 return true;
8246
8247 // Give the external AST source a chance to complete the type.
8248 if (auto *Source = Context.getExternalSource()) {
8249 if (Tag && Tag->hasExternalLexicalStorage())
8250 Source->CompleteType(Tag);
8251 if (IFace && IFace->hasExternalLexicalStorage())
8252 Source->CompleteType(IFace);
8253 // If the external source completed the type, go through the motions
8254 // again to ensure we're allowed to use the completed type.
8255 if (!T->isIncompleteType())
8256 return RequireCompleteTypeImpl(Loc, T, Diagnoser);
8257 }
8258 }
8259
8260 // If we have a class template specialization or a class member of a
8261 // class template specialization, or an array with known size of such,
8262 // try to instantiate it.
8263 if (auto *RD = dyn_cast_or_null<CXXRecordDecl>(Tag)) {
8264 bool Instantiated = false;
8265 bool Diagnosed = false;
8266 if (RD->isDependentContext()) {
8267 // Don't try to instantiate a dependent class (eg, a member template of
8268 // an instantiated class template specialization).
8269 // FIXME: Can this ever happen?
8270 } else if (auto *ClassTemplateSpec =
8271 dyn_cast<ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl>(RD)) {
8272 if (ClassTemplateSpec->getSpecializationKind() == TSK_Undeclared) {
8273 Diagnosed = InstantiateClassTemplateSpecialization(
8274 Loc, ClassTemplateSpec, TSK_ImplicitInstantiation,
8275 /*Complain=*/Diagnoser);
8276 Instantiated = true;
8277 }
8278 } else {
8279 CXXRecordDecl *Pattern = RD->getInstantiatedFromMemberClass();
8280 if (!RD->isBeingDefined() && Pattern) {
8281 MemberSpecializationInfo *MSI = RD->getMemberSpecializationInfo();
8282 assert(MSI && "Missing member specialization information?");
8283 // This record was instantiated from a class within a template.
8284 if (MSI->getTemplateSpecializationKind() !=
8285 TSK_ExplicitSpecialization) {
8286 Diagnosed = InstantiateClass(Loc, RD, Pattern,
8287 getTemplateInstantiationArgs(RD),
8288 TSK_ImplicitInstantiation,
8289 /*Complain=*/Diagnoser);
8290 Instantiated = true;
8291 }
8292 }
8293 }
8294
8295 if (Instantiated) {
8296 // Instantiate* might have already complained that the template is not
8297 // defined, if we asked it to.
8298 if (Diagnoser && Diagnosed)
8299 return true;
8300 // If we instantiated a definition, check that it's usable, even if
8301 // instantiation produced an error, so that repeated calls to this
8302 // function give consistent answers.
8303 if (!T->isIncompleteType())
8304 return RequireCompleteTypeImpl(Loc, T, Diagnoser);
8305 }
8306 }
8307
8308 // FIXME: If we didn't instantiate a definition because of an explicit
8309 // specialization declaration, check that it's visible.
8310
8311 if (!Diagnoser)
8312 return true;
8313
8314 Diagnoser->diagnose(*this, Loc, T);
8315
8316 // If the type was a forward declaration of a class/struct/union
8317 // type, produce a note.
8318 if (Tag && !Tag->isInvalidDecl())
8319 Diag(Tag->getLocation(),
8320 Tag->isBeingDefined() ? diag::note_type_being_defined
8321 : diag::note_forward_declaration)
8322 << Context.getTagDeclType(Tag);
8323
8324 // If the Objective-C class was a forward declaration, produce a note.
8325 if (IFace && !IFace->isInvalidDecl())
8326 Diag(IFace->getLocation(), diag::note_forward_class);
8327
8328 // If we have external information that we can use to suggest a fix,
8329 // produce a note.
8330 if (ExternalSource)
8331 ExternalSource->MaybeDiagnoseMissingCompleteType(Loc, T);
8332
8333 return true;
8334}
8335
8336bool Sema::RequireCompleteType(SourceLocation Loc, QualType T,
8337 unsigned DiagID) {
8338 BoundTypeDiagnoser<> Diagnoser(DiagID);
8339 return RequireCompleteType(Loc, T, Diagnoser);
8340}
8341
8342/// Get diagnostic %select index for tag kind for
8343/// literal type diagnostic message.
8344/// WARNING: Indexes apply to particular diagnostics only!
8345///
8346/// \returns diagnostic %select index.
8347static unsigned getLiteralDiagFromTagKind(TagTypeKind Tag) {
8348 switch (Tag) {
8349 case TTK_Struct: return 0;
8350 case TTK_Interface: return 1;
8351 case TTK_Class: return 2;
8352 default: llvm_unreachable("Invalid tag kind for literal type diagnostic!");
8353 }
8354}
8355
8356/// Ensure that the type T is a literal type.
8357///
8358/// This routine checks whether the type @p T is a literal type. If @p T is an
8359/// incomplete type, an attempt is made to complete it. If @p T is a literal
8360/// type, or @p AllowIncompleteType is true and @p T is an incomplete type,
8361/// returns false. Otherwise, this routine issues the diagnostic @p PD (giving
8362/// it the type @p T), along with notes explaining why the type is not a
8363/// literal type, and returns true.
8364///
8365/// @param Loc The location in the source that the non-literal type
8366/// diagnostic should refer to.
8367///
8368/// @param T The type that this routine is examining for literalness.
8369///
8370/// @param Diagnoser Emits a diagnostic if T is not a literal type.
8371///
8372/// @returns @c true if @p T is not a literal type and a diagnostic was emitted,
8373/// @c false otherwise.
8374bool Sema::RequireLiteralType(SourceLocation Loc, QualType T,
8375 TypeDiagnoser &Diagnoser) {
8376 assert(!T->isDependentType() && "type should not be dependent");
8377
8378 QualType ElemType = Context.getBaseElementType(T);
8379 if ((isCompleteType(Loc, ElemType) || ElemType->isVoidType()) &&
8380 T->isLiteralType(Context))
8381 return false;
8382
8383 Diagnoser.diagnose(*this, Loc, T);
8384
8385 if (T->isVariableArrayType())
8386 return true;
8387
8388 const RecordType *RT = ElemType->getAs<RecordType>();
8389 if (!RT)
8390 return true;
8391
8392 const CXXRecordDecl *RD = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(RT->getDecl());
8393
8394 // A partially-defined class type can't be a literal type, because a literal
8395 // class type must have a trivial destructor (which can't be checked until
8396 // the class definition is complete).
8397 if (RequireCompleteType(Loc, ElemType, diag::note_non_literal_incomplete, T))
8398 return true;
8399
8400 // [expr.prim.lambda]p3:
8401 // This class type is [not] a literal type.
8402 if (RD->isLambda() && !getLangOpts().CPlusPlus17) {
8403 Diag(RD->getLocation(), diag::note_non_literal_lambda);
8404 return true;
8405 }
8406
8407 // If the class has virtual base classes, then it's not an aggregate, and
8408 // cannot have any constexpr constructors or a trivial default constructor,
8409 // so is non-literal. This is better to diagnose than the resulting absence
8410 // of constexpr constructors.
8411 if (RD->getNumVBases()) {
8412 Diag(RD->getLocation(), diag::note_non_literal_virtual_base)
8413 << getLiteralDiagFromTagKind(RD->getTagKind()) << RD->getNumVBases();
8414 for (const auto &I : RD->vbases())
8415 Diag(I.getBeginLoc(), diag::note_constexpr_virtual_base_here)
8416 << I.getSourceRange();
8417 } else if (!RD->isAggregate() && !RD->hasConstexprNonCopyMoveConstructor() &&
8418 !RD->hasTrivialDefaultConstructor()) {
8419 Diag(RD->getLocation(), diag::note_non_literal_no_constexpr_ctors) << RD;
8420 } else if (RD->hasNonLiteralTypeFieldsOrBases()) {
8421 for (const auto &I : RD->bases()) {
8422 if (!I.getType()->isLiteralType(Context)) {
8423 Diag(I.getBeginLoc(), diag::note_non_literal_base_class)
8424 << RD << I.getType() << I.getSourceRange();
8425 return true;
8426 }
8427 }
8428 for (const auto *I : RD->fields()) {
8429 if (!I->getType()->isLiteralType(Context) ||
8430 I->getType().isVolatileQualified()) {
8431 Diag(I->getLocation(), diag::note_non_literal_field)
8432 << RD << I << I->getType()
8433 << I->getType().isVolatileQualified();
8434 return true;
8435 }
8436 }
8437 } else if (!RD->hasTrivialDestructor()) {
8438 // All fields and bases are of literal types, so have trivial destructors.
8439 // If this class's destructor is non-trivial it must be user-declared.
8440 CXXDestructorDecl *Dtor = RD->getDestructor();
8441 assert(Dtor && "class has literal fields and bases but no dtor?");
8442 if (!Dtor)
8443 return true;
8444
8445 Diag(Dtor->getLocation(), Dtor->isUserProvided() ?
8446 diag::note_non_literal_user_provided_dtor :
8447 diag::note_non_literal_nontrivial_dtor) << RD;
8448 if (!Dtor->isUserProvided())
8449 SpecialMemberIsTrivial(Dtor, CXXDestructor, TAH_IgnoreTrivialABI,
8450 /*Diagnose*/true);
8451 }
8452
8453 return true;
8454}
8455
8456bool Sema::RequireLiteralType(SourceLocation Loc, QualType T, unsigned DiagID) {
8457 BoundTypeDiagnoser<> Diagnoser(DiagID);
8458 return RequireLiteralType(Loc, T, Diagnoser);
8459}
8460
8461/// Retrieve a version of the type 'T' that is elaborated by Keyword, qualified
8462/// by the nested-name-specifier contained in SS, and that is (re)declared by
8463/// OwnedTagDecl, which is nullptr if this is not a (re)declaration.
8464QualType Sema::getElaboratedType(ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword,
8465 const CXXScopeSpec &SS, QualType T,
8466 TagDecl *OwnedTagDecl) {
8467 if (T.isNull())
8468 return T;
8469 NestedNameSpecifier *NNS;
8470 if (SS.isValid())
8471 NNS = SS.getScopeRep();
8472 else {
8473 if (Keyword == ETK_None)
8474 return T;
8475 NNS = nullptr;
8476 }
8477 return Context.getElaboratedType(Keyword, NNS, T, OwnedTagDecl);
8478}
8479
8480QualType Sema::BuildTypeofExprType(Expr *E, SourceLocation Loc) {
8481 assert(!E->hasPlaceholderType() && "unexpected placeholder");
8482
8483 if (!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus && E->refersToBitField())
8484 Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag::err_sizeof_alignof_typeof_bitfield) << 2;
8485
8486 if (!E->isTypeDependent()) {
8487 QualType T = E->getType();
8488 if (const TagType *TT = T->getAs<TagType>())
8489 DiagnoseUseOfDecl(TT->getDecl(), E->getExprLoc());
8490 }
8491 return Context.getTypeOfExprType(E);
8492}
8493
8494/// getDecltypeForExpr - Given an expr, will return the decltype for
8495/// that expression, according to the rules in C++11
8496/// [dcl.type.simple]p4 and C++11 [expr.lambda.prim]p18.
8497static QualType getDecltypeForExpr(Sema &S, Expr *E) {
8498 if (E->isTypeDependent())
8499 return S.Context.DependentTy;
8500
8501 // C++11 [dcl.type.simple]p4:
8502 // The type denoted by decltype(e) is defined as follows:
8503 //
8504 // - if e is an unparenthesized id-expression or an unparenthesized class
8505 // member access (5.2.5), decltype(e) is the type of the entity named
8506 // by e. If there is no such entity, or if e names a set of overloaded
8507 // functions, the program is ill-formed;
8508 //
8509 // We apply the same rules for Objective-C ivar and property references.
8510 if (const DeclRefExpr *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E)) {
8511 const ValueDecl *VD = DRE->getDecl();
8512 return VD->getType();
8513 } else if (const MemberExpr *ME = dyn_cast<MemberExpr>(E)) {
8514 if (const ValueDecl *VD = ME->getMemberDecl())
8515 if (isa<FieldDecl>(VD) || isa<VarDecl>(VD))
8516 return VD->getType();
8517 } else if (const ObjCIvarRefExpr *IR = dyn_cast<ObjCIvarRefExpr>(E)) {
8518 return IR->getDecl()->getType();
8519 } else if (const ObjCPropertyRefExpr *PR = dyn_cast<ObjCPropertyRefExpr>(E)) {
8520 if (PR->isExplicitProperty())
8521 return PR->getExplicitProperty()->getType();
8522 } else if (auto *PE = dyn_cast<PredefinedExpr>(E)) {
8523 return PE->getType();
8524 }
8525
8526 // C++11 [expr.lambda.prim]p18:
8527 // Every occurrence of decltype((x)) where x is a possibly
8528 // parenthesized id-expression that names an entity of automatic
8529 // storage duration is treated as if x were transformed into an
8530 // access to a corresponding data member of the closure type that
8531 // would have been declared if x were an odr-use of the denoted
8532 // entity.
8533 using namespace sema;
8534 if (S.getCurLambda()) {
8535 if (isa<ParenExpr>(E)) {
8536 if (DeclRefExpr *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E->IgnoreParens())) {
8537 if (VarDecl *Var = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(DRE->getDecl())) {
8538 QualType T = S.getCapturedDeclRefType(Var, DRE->getLocation());
8539 if (!T.isNull())
8540 return S.Context.getLValueReferenceType(T);
8541 }
8542 }
8543 }
8544 }
8545
8546
8547 // C++11 [dcl.type.simple]p4:
8548 // [...]
8549 QualType T = E->getType();
8550 switch (E->getValueKind()) {
8551 // - otherwise, if e is an xvalue, decltype(e) is T&&, where T is the
8552 // type of e;
8553 case VK_XValue: T = S.Context.getRValueReferenceType(T); break;
8554 // - otherwise, if e is an lvalue, decltype(e) is T&, where T is the
8555 // type of e;
8556 case VK_LValue: T = S.Context.getLValueReferenceType(T); break;
8557 // - otherwise, decltype(e) is the type of e.
8558 case VK_RValue: break;
8559 }
8560
8561 return T;
8562}
8563
8564QualType Sema::BuildDecltypeType(Expr *E, SourceLocation Loc,
8565 bool AsUnevaluated) {
8566 assert(!E->hasPlaceholderType() && "unexpected placeholder");
8567
8568 if (AsUnevaluated && CodeSynthesisContexts.empty() &&
8569 E->HasSideEffects(Context, false)) {
8570 // The expression operand for decltype is in an unevaluated expression
8571 // context, so side effects could result in unintended consequences.
8572 Diag(E->getExprLoc(), diag::warn_side_effects_unevaluated_context);
8573 }
8574
8575 return Context.getDecltypeType(E, getDecltypeForExpr(*this, E));
8576}
8577
8578QualType Sema::BuildUnaryTransformType(QualType BaseType,
8579 UnaryTransformType::UTTKind UKind,
8580 SourceLocation Loc) {
8581 switch (UKind) {
8582 case UnaryTransformType::EnumUnderlyingType:
8583 if (!BaseType->isDependentType() && !BaseType->isEnumeralType()) {
8584 Diag(Loc, diag::err_only_enums_have_underlying_types);
8585 return QualType();
8586 } else {
8587 QualType Underlying = BaseType;
8588 if (!BaseType->isDependentType()) {
8589 // The enum could be incomplete if we're parsing its definition or
8590 // recovering from an error.
8591 NamedDecl *FwdDecl = nullptr;
8592 if (BaseType->isIncompleteType(&FwdDecl)) {
8593 Diag(Loc, diag::err_underlying_type_of_incomplete_enum) << BaseType;
8594 Diag(FwdDecl->getLocation(), diag::note_forward_declaration) << FwdDecl;
8595 return QualType();
8596 }
8597
8598 EnumDecl *ED = BaseType->getAs<EnumType>()->getDecl();
8599 assert(ED && "EnumType has no EnumDecl");
8600
8601 DiagnoseUseOfDecl(ED, Loc);
8602
8603 Underlying = ED->getIntegerType();
8604 assert(!Underlying.isNull());
8605 }
8606 return Context.getUnaryTransformType(BaseType, Underlying,
8607 UnaryTransformType::EnumUnderlyingType);
8608 }
8609 }
8610 llvm_unreachable("unknown unary transform type");
8611}
8612
8613QualType Sema::BuildAtomicType(QualType T, SourceLocation Loc) {
8614 if (!T->isDependentType()) {
8615 // FIXME: It isn't entirely clear whether incomplete atomic types
8616 // are allowed or not; for simplicity, ban them for the moment.
8617 if (RequireCompleteType(Loc, T, diag::err_atomic_specifier_bad_type, 0))
8618 return QualType();
8619
8620 int DisallowedKind = -1;
8621 if (T->isArrayType())
8622 DisallowedKind = 1;
8623 else if (T->isFunctionType())
8624 DisallowedKind = 2;
8625 else if (T->isReferenceType())
8626 DisallowedKind = 3;
8627 else if (T->isAtomicType())
8628 DisallowedKind = 4;
8629 else if (T.hasQualifiers())
8630 DisallowedKind = 5;
8631 else if (!T.isTriviallyCopyableType(Context))
8632 // Some other non-trivially-copyable type (probably a C++ class)
8633 DisallowedKind = 6;
8634
8635 if (DisallowedKind != -1) {
8636 Diag(Loc, diag::err_atomic_specifier_bad_type) << DisallowedKind << T;
8637 return QualType();
8638 }
8639
8640 // FIXME: Do we need any handling for ARC here?
8641 }
8642
8643 // Build the pointer type.
8644 return Context.getAtomicType(T);
8645}
8646
